By Jonathan Nda- Isaiah, The Naira recently reversed its depreciation trend in the parallel market, due to what observers attributed to the new rules introduced by the Central Bank of Nigeria. The new rule  allow beneficiaries of diaspora remittances and foreign exchange transfers into domiciliary accounts and to collect the proceeds in foreign currencies. This position was contained in a statement by the Ethnic Youth Leaders Council of Nigeria signed by its spokesperson Godwin Meliga and the leaders of Ohanaeze Youth Movement Ochiagha Uche Nnadi, Arewa Consultative Youth Movement Kabiru Yusuf, Niger Delta Youth Council Bassey Henshaw and Odua Youth Assembly Isiaq Bello following the sharp rise in the value of the Naira after the CBN announced the diaspora remittances of foreign exchange to halt the declining value of the naira caused by shortage of Forex. The group which comprises youth leaders of over four hundred ethnic nationalities in Nigeria hailed the CBN Governor for his vision and boldness in directing the policy and reversing the downward trend of the Naira. The policy the group maintained has boosted the economy and made it viable yet again. It has made prices of certain levels of good which are imported into the country cheaper hence having spiral effect on several other products and the economy generally. The Council therefore restated its conviction that the Godwin Emefiele led central Bank of Nigeria is capable of drawing the country out of its latest recession, described as its worst recession in several decades, in record time having shown capacity effectiveness to do so. 